{"description": "In the occlusal view of the lower arch, the photograph captures the mandibular teeth from the right second molar (#38) across to the left second molar (#48). The overall hue of the dentition is a warm yellowish tone, suggesting a degree of natural staining consistent with age or dietary factors. The gingival margins are pink, stippled, and appear healthy, with a smooth, scalloped contour that follows the cervical outlines of the teeth. The alveolar ridge is intact and shows no signs of recession or bony exposure.

The occlusal surfaces of the posterior teeth display the expected anatomy: well‑defined cusps, central fossae, and marginal ridges. Most of the teeth look intact, with no visible restorations, fractures, or attrition beyond the normal wear pattern. However, in the pits and fissures of the occlusal surfaces of the right second premolar (#37), right first molar (#38), left second premolar (#47), and left second molar (#48), there is a distinct black pigmentation. This discoloration is confined to the deep grooves and appears as irregular, matte spots, likely representing extrinsic staining or possibly early melan melanin deposition, but no cavitation is evident.

