{"description": "In this frontal intraoral photograph the patient’s mouth is opened wide enough to display the full complement of anterior teeth in both arches, allowing a clear view of the hard and soft tissues. The maxillary anterior segment (teeth numbered 13 to 23) shows a heavy, dark brown coating of plaque and calculus covering the labial surfaces, with additional soft debris accumulated in the interproximal areas. The mandibic gingiva surrounding these teeth is markedly erythematous and swollen, and on gentle probing there is localized bleeding, indicating acute inflammation. The upper canines (teeth 13 and 23) are noticeably tipped labially, giving them a proclined appearance that further accentuates the plaque buildup on their crowns.

